2","1417":"1417","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stedman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Steadman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Steadman","meanings":["English:","occupational or topographic name from Middle English <i>stede</i> ‘place, farm, estate’ (Old English <i>stede</i>) + <i>-man</i>, used for someone who lived or worked on a farm, or who lived at a place so named. Compare   Stead  .","occupational name for someone who worked with horses, from Middle English <i>sted(e)</i> ‘horse, stallion’ (Old English <i>steda</i>) + <i>-man</i>. Compare   Steed  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Stedman was born in 1392, his father, John De Le Stede, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. John De Le Stede, was 30. He had at least 1 son with Dorcas J.."},"et":{"1392–":"1392–Surnud","1387–1417":"1387–1417","1392–Male":"1392–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1422–1477":"1422–1477","1361–Male":"1361–Surnud","1363–Female":"1363–Surnud","1422":"1422","1477":"1477","1387":"1387","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1392":"1392","1417":"1417"},"fi":{"1392–":"1392–Kuollut","1387–1417":"1387–1417","1392–Male":"1392–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1422–1477":"1422–147